  "body": "Reported by Bittrex\r\n\r\n#### System information\r\n\r\nGeth version: `1.7.2`\r\nOS & Version: unknown\r\nCommit hash : unknown\r\n\r\n#### Expected behaviour\r\n\r\nsendTransaction() always retrieves correct nonce\r\n\r\n#### Actual behaviour\r\n\r\nsendTransaction() sometimes retrieves a nonce which looks like belonging to a different account.\r\n\r\n#### Steps to reproduce the behaviour\r\n\r\nDifficult to reproduce, happens very rarely when sending lots of transactions using sendTransaction()\r\n\r\n#### Backtrace\r\n\r\nNot available\r\n\r\n#### Suspected cause\r\nI have analysed the code in https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/v1.7.2/core/tx_pool.go, specifically how \"TxPool.pendingState\" and \"TxPool.currentState\" are used. I have checked all code paths, and they always under the same lock (TxPool.mu), except when the function \"TxPool.State()\" is called (from https://github.com/ethereum/go-ethereum/blob/v1.7.2/eth/api_backend.go#L160). Function \"GetNonce\" is called on the managed state without any locks, and it can happen concurrently with the TxPool loop making modifications to \"TxPool.pendingState\". What most probably happened was resizing/rehashing of the hash map that stores state objects, and during that rehashing RPC call read a nonce from a different account.\r\n",
